  <section>
    <h2>var vs em vs code</h2>
    <p>All three render distinctly in VB:</p>
    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Element</th>
          <th>Rendering</th>
          <th>Use Case</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;var&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Italic + <code>--color-interactive</code></td>
          <td>Variables, placeholders</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;em&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Italic only</td>
          <td>Stress emphasis</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;code&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Monospace + background</td>
          <td>Code identifiers, inline code</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CSS Reference</h2>
    <code-block language="css" show-lines label="var CSS">{{ varCssCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>The accent color makes variables scannable in technical prose without the visual weight of <code>&lt;code&gt;</code>'s background. The <code>translate: no</code> prevents machine translation from mangling variable names.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Screen readers do not announce <code>&lt;var&gt;</code> differently from surrounding text</li>
      <li>The accent color is a visual cue only &mdash; context should make the variable clear</li>
      <li>For complex math where variables are critical, consider MathML or <code>aria-label</code></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

